#compdef pigo
# =============================================================================
# pigo — Endre Simo's "Fast face detection, pupil/eyes
#          localization and facial landmark points
#          detection library in pure Go" — a Go-native
#          face-detection CLI built around the Pixel
#          Intensity Comparison Object (PICO) cascade
#          algorithm by Markuš et al. (2014), with NO
#          OpenCV dependency, NO C bindings, and NO
#          external native libraries — everything runs
#          on the pure-Go image-decoding stack.
#          Distinguishing from OpenCV (the dominant
#          C++/Python face-detection library that requires
#          a C-toolchain + the heavyweight ~50 MB libcv
#          install), dlib (C++ library with Python
#          bindings, also heavy), face_recognition
#          (Adam Geitgey's Python dlib wrapper), MediaPipe
#          (Google's cross-platform ML pipeline with
#          TFLite runtime), and FaceAPI.js (Vincent
#          Mühler's TensorFlow.js port) by:
#            - PURE GO — single statically-linked binary
#              with NO native dependencies; cross-compiles
#              to any GOOS/GOARCH supported by the Go
#              toolchain (linux/amd64, linux/arm64,
#              darwin/arm64, windows/amd64, freebsd, …)
#              from a single host
#            - PICO ALGORITHM — uses the Pixel Intensity
#              Comparison Object cascade from Nenad
#              Markuš's 2014 paper "Object Detection with
#              Pixel Intensity Comparisons Organized in
#              Decision Trees" (originally implemented in
#              C as `pico`); pigo is the canonical Go
#              port maintained by Endre Simo since 2017
#            - DISINTEGRATION/IMAGING — uses Grigory
#              Dryapak's disintegration/imaging Go
#              package (this is the headline CLI library
#              that CONTINUES Axis 40 on the Go side; see
#              taxonomy notes below) for image loading
#              (PNG/JPEG decode via Go stdlib +
#              orientation/EXIF handling), color-space
#              conversion to grayscale (PICO operates on
#              luminance values), and resize operations
#              for multi-scale detection windows
#            - FOGLEMAN/GG DRAWING — uses Michael
#              Fogleman's fogleman/gg Go graphics library
#              (cairo-like 2D rendering surface) to
#              composite detected face markers (rectangle/
#              circle/ellipse) onto the output image with
#              configurable colors + line widths
#            - CASCADE-FILE-DRIVEN — `-cf <facefinder>`
#              loads a binary Haar-cascade-like file
#              (provided in `cascade/facefinder` in the
#              repo, ~2 MB).  Additional `-plc` (pupils
#              localization cascade) + `-flpc` (facial
#              landmark points cascade directory) enable
#              eye + landmark detection
#            - MULTI-ANGLE DETECTION — `-angle <0..1>`
#              rotates the detection window from 0
#              radians (`0.0`) to 2π radians (`1.0`),
#              enabling detection of faces tilted at
#              arbitrary angles (useful for video frames
#              where heads are rotated)
#            - IoU NON-MAX SUPPRESSION — `-iou <float>`
#              sets the Intersection-over-Union
#              threshold for non-maximum suppression of
#              overlapping detections (default 0.15);
#              tighter values produce more (potentially
#              duplicate) detections, looser values
#              prune more aggressively
#            - SLIDING WINDOW TUNING — `-shift <float>`
#              + `-scale <float>` control the detection-
#              window shift step + scale increment
#              between cascade passes; defaults 0.15 +
#              1.15 balance detection rate vs runtime
#            - SIZE BOUNDS — `-min` + `-max` clip the
#              face size search range; tight bounds
#              (e.g. min=80 max=120) dramatically speed
#              up detection when face size is known a
#              priori (e.g. selfie cameras at fixed
#              distance)
#            - JSON OUTPUT MODE — `-json <out.json>`
#              emits detection coordinates (face
#              bounding box, eye points, landmark
#              points) as structured JSON for
#              downstream pipeline consumption — no need
#              to scrape the rendered image
#            - DETECTION MARKER SHAPES — `-marker
#              rect|circle|ellipse` chooses the overlay
#              geometry; ellipse approximates the face
#              outline; rect is fastest to draw; circle
#              is decorative
#            - STDIN/STDOUT PIPE MODE — `-in -` + `-out
#              -` (the `-` pseudo-filename) lets pigo
#              participate in shell pipelines: `cat
#              input.jpg | pigo -cf facefinder -in - -
#              out - > out.png`
#            - WASM PORT — the same Go codebase
#              compiles to WebAssembly (see `wasm/`
#              dir) for in-browser face detection,
#              demonstrating that the pure-Go approach
#              extends naturally to browser runtimes
#            - 4,701+ STARS ON esimov/pigo — one of the
#              most popular Go image-ML projects in the
#              ecosystem
#          Used by: photo-management tools that want to
#          auto-tag people without shipping OpenCV (avoid
#          the ~50 MB native-library footprint), serverless
#          face-detection functions (AWS Lambda / Cloud
#          Functions where statically-linked Go binaries
#          deploy trivially), real-time video-processing
#          pipelines tuned for low-latency inference (no
#          PyTorch/TensorFlow runtime overhead), and
#          privacy-conscious deployments where running
#          face detection on-device + on-premises is
#          required by data-residency rules.
#
# Author:  Endre Simo (esimov on GitHub; www.esimov.com),
#          Romanian software developer.  Also author of
#          triangle (image triangulation in Go),
#          ascii-image-converter, gomp (gomp image
#          processing).
# Source:  https://github.com/esimov/pigo
#          https://github.com/esimov/pigo/blob/master/cmd/pigo/main.go
#          https://github.com/esimov/pigo/blob/master/go.mod
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `pigo` with no `-in`
#          + `-cf` prints usage from its custom
#          flag.Usage handler.  Full algorithm + usage
#          docs in repo README.md.
# Library: github.com/disintegration/imaging v1.6.2 —
#          Grigory Dryapak's "Go image processing
#          package" (the headline dependency for this
#          completion's axis-40 continuation role; see
#          taxonomy notes below).  Also github.com/
#          fogleman/gg v1.3.0 (Michael Fogleman's
#          cairo-like 2D graphics for marker drawing),
#          golang.org/x/term (terminal control for
#          spinner progress indicator), Go stdlib's
#          encoding/json + flag + image/{png,jpeg,
#          color} packages.
# License: MIT
# Status:  4,701+ stars on esimov/pigo; actively
#          maintained (latest commit 2026-06-01);
#          stable v1.x release line.
#
